{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784626472563,"sessionID":"ses_07c1fcf6effe2YUDoq6jbB4HYf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_eF6tZwTv4DmJ8220F8laS5J1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Dashboard\n2: \n3: ## Iteration Table\n4: \n5: | run | focus | newInfoRatio | findings | status |\n6: |---:|---|---:|---:|---|\n7: | 1 | Shipped command anatomy and literal-prompt gap | 0.90 | 5 | complete |\n8: | 2 | Runtime include/shared-fragment mechanism | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n9: | 3 | Five literal body cores and content ownership | 0.90 | 5 | complete |\n10: | 4 | Adversarial conformance and corrections | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n11: \n12: ## Question Status\n13: \n14: - Answered: 5 / 5 required questions\n15: - Carried forward: exact project-root include spelling needs an isolated live fixture.\n16: \n17: ## Convergence Trend\n18: \n19: - Ratios: 0.90 -> 1.00 -> 0.90 -> 1.00\n20: - Minimum-iteration guard: passed after iteration 3.\n21: - Stop policy: `max-iterations`; convergence is telemetry only until iteration 5.\n22: - Stuck count: 0\n23: \n24: ## Dead Ends\n25: \n26: - Broad repository searches over generic include/template terms are too noisy.\n27: - Wholesale router replacement and command-owned taste doctrine are eliminated.\n28: - Markdown/read references are not loader includes; shell rendering and full hand duplication are unnecessary.\n29: - Design-reference must not inherit originality rhetoric; reference inventories and transport mechanics stay mode-owned.\n30: - `ASK` must remain; presentations cannot remain a competing normative prompt authority; audit cannot mutate; design-reference token tables are measured-only.\n31: \n32: ## Next Focus\n33: \n34: Resolve include spelling from strongest available evidence and finalize synthesis-ready acceptance criteria.\n35: \n36: ## Active Risks\n37: \n38: - `@./path` runtime expansion still needs a representative live command-dispatch fixture during implementation.\n39: - Literal richness must not fork mode-owned taste doctrine.\n40: - Documentation proves `@` inclusion but not the exact `@./.opencode/...` resolution base; a live fixture is still required before merge.\n\n(End of file - total 40 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Dashboard\n\n## Iteration Table\n\n| run | focus | newInfoRatio | findings | status |\n|---:|---|---:|---:|---|\n| 1 | Shipped command anatomy and literal-prompt gap | 0.90 | 5 | complete |\n| 2 | Runtime include/shared-fragment mechanism | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n| 3 | Five literal body cores and content ownership | 0.90 | 5 | complete |\n| 4 | Adversarial conformance and corrections | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n\n## Question Status\n\n- Answered: 5 / 5 required questions\n- Carried forward: exact project-root include spelling needs an isolated live fixture.\n\n## Convergence Trend\n\n- Ratios: 0.90 -> 1.00 -> 0.90 -> 1.00\n- Minimum-iteration guard: passed after iteration 3.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md","text":"# Deep Research Dashboard\n\n## Iteration Table\n\n| run | focus | newInfoRatio | findings | status |\n|---:|---|---:|---:|---|\n| 1 | Shipped command anatomy and literal-prompt gap | 0.90 | 5 | complete |\n| 2 | Runtime include/shared-fragment mechanism | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n| 3 | Five literal body cores and content ownership | 0.90 | 5 | complete |\n| 4 | Adversarial conformance and corrections | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n\n## Question Status\n\n- Answered: 5 / 5 required questions\n- Carried forward: exact project-root include spelling needs an isolated live fixture.\n\n## Convergence Trend\n\n- Ratios: 0.90 -> 1.00 -> 0.90 -> 1.00\n- Minimum-iteration guard: passed after iteration 3.\n- Stop policy: `max-iterations`; convergence is telemetry only until iteration 5.\n- Stuck count: 0\n\n## Dead Ends\n\n- Broad repository searches over generic include/template terms are too noisy.\n- Wholesale router replacement and command-owned taste doctrine are eliminated.\n- Markdown/read references are not loader includes; shell rendering and full hand duplication are unnecessary.\n- Design-reference must not inherit originality rhetoric; reference inventories and transport mechanics stay mode-owned.\n- `ASK` must remain; presentations cannot remain a competing normative prompt authority; audit cannot mutate; design-reference token tables are measured-only.\n\n## Next Focus\n\nResolve include spelling from strongest available evidence and finalize synthesis-ready acceptance criteria.\n\n## Active Risks\n\n- `@./path` runtime expansion still needs a representative live command-dispatch fixture during implementation.\n- Literal richness must not fork mode-owned taste doctrine.\n- Documentation proves `@` inclusion but not the exact `@./.opencode/...` resolution base; a live fixture is still required before merge.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":40,"totalLines":40,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md","time":{"start":1784626472526,"end":1784626472554}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0201d8e03d6151bd016a5f3d28308081918f6690ada1a1be29"}},"id":"prt_f8406e64b001UVNc6qTwGKGsIH","sessionID":"ses_07c1fcf6effe2YUDoq6jbB4HYf","messageID":"msg_f84068f1e001277goGF4Jwuu3r"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784626472563,"sessionID":"ses_07c1fcf6effe2YUDoq6jbB4HYf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ETIl4QJuGQH4XoYGKkAl42gQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"openQuestions\": [\"What exact project-root spelling should the isolated live include fixture promote?\"],\n3:   \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n4:     \"What exactly do the shipped command routers, presentation assets, and shared creation contract contain, and which literal-prompt qualities are absent?\",\n5:     \"What include/shared-fragment mechanism does the runtime support?\",\n6:     \"What complete literal body should each of the five commands contain?\",\n7:     \"Which content stays literal, shared, or mode-owned?\",\n8:     \"What file/change/test sequence can ship the rewrite safely?\"\n9:   ],\n10:   \"keyFindings\": [\n11:     {\"id\":\"I001-F1\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The five shipped bodies are substantial mode routers, not self-contained creation prompts.\"},\n12:     {\"id\":\"I001-F2\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Command-specific intake, sibling discrimination, stable mappings, and typed products are working architecture worth preserving.\"},\n13:     {\"id\":\"I001-F3\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Presentation assets implement progressive intake and visible lifecycle blocks but fragment prompt wording away from command bodies.\"},\n14:     {\"id\":\"I001-F4\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The skill-local creation contract centralizes choreography and authority while intentionally excluding design taste.\"},\n15:     {\"id\":\"I001-F5\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The remaining gap is an evocative, actionable, command-visible creation brief, not missing routing architecture.\"},\n16:     {\"id\":\"I002-F1\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"@./path is the smallest direct runtime file-content expansion mechanism; it makes the rendered prompt, not the checked-in command bytes, self-contained.\"},\n17:     {\"id\":\"I002-F2\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"$ARGUMENTS preserves invocation intake but is not a shared-fragment mechanism.\"},\n18:     {\"id\":\"I002-F3\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shell-output rendering is feasible but introduces disproportionate registry, drift, rollout, security, and manifest machinery.\"},\n19:     {\"id\":\"I002-F4\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Generation is required only if every checked-in command must contain all canonical shared bytes.\"},\n20:     {\"id\":\"I002-F5\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Use a literal mode-specific creation brief plus one @ reference to the shared normative creation contract.\"},\n21:     {\"id\":\"I003-F1\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Literal command bodies should own the mode-specific mission, progressive intake, ordered work, critique rule, evidence ceiling, and typed product while delegating taste.\"},\n22:     {\"id\":\"I003-F2\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"One canonical @ expansion carries shared lifecycle and schemas without five-copy drift.\"},\n23:     {\"id\":\"I003-F3\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"A three-way placement rule separates literal public orchestration, shared normative schemas, and mode-owned judgment.\"},\n24:     {\"id\":\"I003-F4\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"All five bodies can share one structural grammar while retaining distinct decisive quality rules.\"},\n25:     {\"id\":\"I003-F5\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Design-reference substitutes source fidelity and provenance for anti-generic creative originality.\"},\n26:     {\"id\":\"I004-F1\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Keep mode-specific missions and local fields, but move universal lifecycle, intake schemas, output blocks, proof labels, and handoff continuity to the shared contract.\"},\n27:     {\"id\":\"I004-F2\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"The proposed OK|DEFER|FAIL shorthand regresses the required STATUS=ASK path.\"},\n28:     {\"id\":\"I004-F3\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Suffix behavior and prompt ownership must be changed atomically because literal wrapper prompts conflict with current presentation-owned wording.\"},\n29:     {\"id\":\"I004-F4\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Audit remains review-only; md-generator alone may write artifacts and only measured values may enter token tables.\"},\n30:     {\"id\":\"I004-F5\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Safe shipment requires an include-root fixture, test-first body invariants, atomic package ownership edits, and suffix/status/mutation negative cases.\"}\n31:   ],\n32:   \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n33:     \"Replace the working routers wholesale\",\n34:     \"Copy mode-owned taste doctrine into commands\",\n35:     \"Treat presentation assets or the shared contract alone as the literal-prompt deliverable\",\n36:     \"Use Markdown links or read imperatives as loader includes\",\n37:     \"Use a shell-command renderer as the smallest mechanism\",\n38:     \"Hand-duplicate the complete shared lifecycle\",\n39:     \"Copy mode-owned reference inventories or transport mechanics into commands\",\n40:     \"Apply anti-generic creation rhetoric to source-faithful extraction\",\n41:     \"Drop STATUS=ASK from literal bodies\",\n42:     \"Keep presentations as a competing normative prompt authority\",\n43:     \"Allow audit to apply fixes\",\n44:     \"Allow brief-provided values into design-reference token tables\",\n45:     \"Claim exact @./ rooting without a live fixture\"\n46:   ],\n47:   \"metrics\": {\n48:     \"iterationsCompleted\": 4,\n49:     \"openQuestions\": 1,\n50:     \"resolvedQuestions\": 5,\n51:     \"keyFindings\": 20,\n52:     \"convergenceScore\": 0.9,\n53:     \"coverageBySources\": {\"commands\":7,\"presentations\":5,\"shared-contract\":1,\"prior-research\":2,\"runtime-docs\":3,\"runtime-code\":2,\"runtime-tests\":3,\"external-docs\":1,\"mode-contracts\":5,\"metadata\":2}\n54:   },\n55:   \"status\": \"iterating\",\n56:   \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784623934648-kt3qkt\",\n57:   \"generation\": 1,\n58:   \"lastUpdated\": \"2026-07-21T09:22:02Z\"\n59: }\n\n(End of file - total 59 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"openQuestions\": [\"What exact project-root spelling should the isolated live include fixture promote?\"],\n  \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n    \"What exactly do the shipped command routers, presentation assets, and shared creation contract contain, and which literal-prompt qualities are absent?\",\n    \"What include/shared-fragment mechanism does the runtime support?\",\n    \"What complete literal body should each of the five commands contain?\",\n    \"Which content stays literal, shared, or mode-owned?\",\n    \"What file/change/test sequence can ship the rewrite safely?\"\n  ],\n  \"keyFindings\": [\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F1\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The five shipped bodies are substantial mode routers, not self-contained creation prompts.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F2\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Command-specific intake, sibling discrimination, stable mappings, and typed products are working architecture worth preserving.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F3\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Presentation assets implement progressive intake and visible lifecycle blocks but fragment prompt wording away from command bodies.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F4\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The skill-local creation contract centralizes choreography and authority while intentionally excluding design taste.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F5\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The remaining gap is an evocative, actionable, command-visible creation brief, not missing routing architecture.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F1\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"@./path is the smallest direct runtime file-content expansion mechanism; it makes the rendered prompt, not the checked-in command bytes, self-contained.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F2\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"$ARGUMENTS preserves invocation intake but is not a shared-fragment mechanism.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F3\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shell-output rendering is feasible but introduces disproportionate registry, drift, rollout, security, and manifest machinery.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F4\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Generation is required only if every checked-in command must contain all canonical shared bytes.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F5\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Use a literal mode-specific creation brief plus one @ reference to the shared normative creation contract.\"},","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","text":"{\n  \"openQuestions\": [\"What exact project-root spelling should the isolated live include fixture promote?\"],\n  \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n    \"What exactly do the shipped command routers, presentation assets, and shared creation contract contain, and which literal-prompt qualities are absent?\",\n    \"What include/shared-fragment mechanism does the runtime support?\",\n    \"What complete literal body should each of the five commands contain?\",\n    \"Which content stays literal, shared, or mode-owned?\",\n    \"What file/change/test sequence can ship the rewrite safely?\"\n  ],\n  \"keyFindings\": [\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F1\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The five shipped bodies are substantial mode routers, not self-contained creation prompts.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F2\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Command-specific intake, sibling discrimination, stable mappings, and typed products are working architecture worth preserving.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F3\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Presentation assets implement progressive intake and visible lifecycle blocks but fragment prompt wording away from command bodies.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F4\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The skill-local creation contract centralizes choreography and authority while intentionally excluding design taste.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I001-F5\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"The remaining gap is an evocative, actionable, command-visible creation brief, not missing routing architecture.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F1\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"@./path is the smallest direct runtime file-content expansion mechanism; it makes the rendered prompt, not the checked-in command bytes, self-contained.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F2\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"$ARGUMENTS preserves invocation intake but is not a shared-fragment mechanism.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F3\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shell-output rendering is feasible but introduces disproportionate registry, drift, rollout, security, and manifest machinery.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F4\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Generation is required only if every checked-in command must contain all canonical shared bytes.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I002-F5\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Use a literal mode-specific creation brief plus one @ reference to the shared normative creation contract.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I003-F1\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Literal command bodies should own the mode-specific mission, progressive intake, ordered work, critique rule, evidence ceiling, and typed product while delegating taste.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I003-F2\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"One canonical @ expansion carries shared lifecycle and schemas without five-copy drift.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I003-F3\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"A three-way placement rule separates literal public orchestration, shared normative schemas, and mode-owned judgment.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I003-F4\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"All five bodies can share one structural grammar while retaining distinct decisive quality rules.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I003-F5\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Design-reference substitutes source fidelity and provenance for anti-generic creative originality.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I004-F1\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Keep mode-specific missions and local fields, but move universal lifecycle, intake schemas, output blocks, proof labels, and handoff continuity to the shared contract.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I004-F2\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"The proposed OK|DEFER|FAIL shorthand regresses the required STATUS=ASK path.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I004-F3\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Suffix behavior and prompt ownership must be changed atomically because literal wrapper prompts conflict with current presentation-owned wording.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I004-F4\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Audit remains review-only; md-generator alone may write artifacts and only measured values may enter token tables.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"I004-F5\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Safe shipment requires an include-root fixture, test-first body invariants, atomic package ownership edits, and suffix/status/mutation negative cases.\"}\n  ],\n  \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n    \"Replace the working routers wholesale\",\n    \"Copy mode-owned taste doctrine into commands\",\n    \"Treat presentation assets or the shared contract alone as the literal-prompt deliverable\",\n    \"Use Markdown links or read imperatives as loader includes\",\n    \"Use a shell-command renderer as the smallest mechanism\",\n    \"Hand-duplicate the complete shared lifecycle\",\n    \"Copy mode-owned reference inventories or transport mechanics into commands\",\n    \"Apply anti-generic creation rhetoric to source-faithful extraction\",\n    \"Drop STATUS=ASK from literal bodies\",\n    \"Keep presentations as a competing normative prompt authority\",\n    \"Allow audit to apply fixes\",\n    \"Allow brief-provided values into design-reference token tables\",\n    \"Claim exact @./ rooting without a live fixture\"\n  ],\n  \"metrics\": {\n    \"iterationsCompleted\": 4,\n    \"openQuestions\": 1,\n    \"resolvedQuestions\": 5,\n    \"keyFindings\": 20,\n    \"convergenceScore\": 0.9,\n    \"coverageBySources\": {\"commands\":7,\"presentations\":5,\"shared-contract\":1,\"prior-research\":2,\"runtime-docs\":3,\"runtime-code\":2,\"runtime-tests\":3,\"external-docs\":1,\"mode-contracts\":5,\"metadata\":2}\n  },\n  \"status\": \"iterating\",\n  \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784623934648-kt3qkt\",\n  \"generation\": 1,\n  \"lastUpdated\": \"2026-07-21T09:22:02Z\"\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":59,"totalLines":59,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","time":{"start":1784626472521,"end":1784626472556}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0201d8e03d6151bd016a5f3d28307081919d45eeb72b9aefee"}},"id":"prt_f8406e634001DPnYTUkseUDAB6","sessionID":"ses_07c1fcf6effe2YUDoq6jbB4HYf","messageID":"msg_f84068f1e001277goGF4Jwuu3r"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784626472563,"sessionID":"ses_07c1fcf6effe2YUDoq6jbB4HYf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_TNnyY6EgyABr1N8WVjCl8ZqX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Strategy: Literal Interface Command Prompts\n2: \n3: ## 1. Research Topic\n4: \n5: Rewrite the five `/interface:*` commands as literal, self-contained design prompts while preserving the split where commands own intake and lifecycle, `sk-design` modes own taste and judgment, transports own realization, and `sk-code` owns application-code mutation.\n6: \n7: ## 2. Non-Goals\n8: \n9: - Do not modify commands, presentation assets, skills, workflows, tests, or packet docs.\n10: - Do not write anywhere outside this detached `sol-high-fast` lineage.\n11: - Do not reopen the settled five-command namespace or stable workflow-mode mapping without contradictory evidence.\n12: - Do not duplicate palettes, typography prescriptions, style menus, reference inventories, or mode-owned taste doctrine into commands.\n13: - Do not settle unrelated styles-library structure or database-fate work.\n14: \n15: ## 3. Stop Conditions\n16: \n17: - Complete exactly five iterations because `stopPolicy=max-iterations`.\n18: - Produce concrete, substantially self-contained command-body proposals for all five `/interface:*` commands.\n19: - Resolve the runtime-supported include/shared-fragment mechanism with direct repository evidence.\n20: - Provide a durable authority/anti-duplication rule and a testable implementation plan.\n21: \n22: <!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n23: ## 4. Key Questions (Remaining)\n24: \n25: - [x] What exactly do the shipped command routers, presentation assets, and shared creation contract contain, and which literal-prompt qualities are absent?\n26: - [x] What complete literal body should each of the five commands contain so an agent receives an evocative, actionable creation brief rather than a thin route?\n27: - [x] What include, template injection, renderer, or generated-fragment mechanism does the current command runtime actually support?\n28: - [x] Which content must stay literal in each command, which content may be shared, and which doctrine must remain mode-owned to prevent drift?\n29: - [x] What exact file/change/test sequence can ship the rewrite without breaking route, intake, proof, handoff, or compatibility contracts?\n30: <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n31: \n32: <!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n33: ## 5. Answered Questions\n34: \n35: - The shipped bodies preserve valuable command-specific intake, sibling discrimination, route proof, stable mode mappings, typed outputs, and mutation boundaries, but outsource the creation experience across presentations and the shared contract. The missing layer is a command-visible, evocative, actionable brief with experiential stakes, anti-generic constraints, real context/content, and a mode-specific quality bar. (iteration 1)\n36: - OpenCode command templates support direct `@./path` file-content expansion. The recommended mechanism is literal, mode-specific creation prose in each command plus one `@./.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/creation-contract.md` expansion for shared normative lifecycle and authority content. This yields runtime-expanded self-containment; checked-in source-byte duplication would require generation and is unnecessary. (iteration 2)\n37: - Five concrete body cores now define the command-visible mission, intake, grounding, stable route, ordered work, targeted revision, proof ceiling, typed output, and handoff for design, foundations, motion, audit, and design-reference. Public orchestration stays literal, universal schemas arrive through the shared `@` contract, and values/judgment remain mode-owned. (iteration 3)\n38: - Adversarial review preserved the missions and mode-specific quality rules but moved universal intake schemas, common blocks, targeted revision, evidence labels, and handoff continuity back to the shared contract. It restored `ASK`, required literal suffix control, made audit review-only, and restricted design-reference token tables to measured values. The safe shipment is test-first and atomic across wrappers, presentation/YAML ownership declarations, and metadata projections. (iteration 4)\n39: <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n40: \n41: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n42: <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n43: ## 6. What Worked\n44: \n45: - Exact cross-command anchor comparison separated the shared routing skeleton from meaningful domain-specific intake and exposed the missing prompt layer without discarding working architecture. (iteration 1)\n46: - Exact command-authoring and renderer-symbol tracing distinguished native `@` expansion, `$ARGUMENTS` substitution, shell rendering, and generated-router patterns. (iteration 2)\n47: - A common mission-to-handoff grammar plus one decisive mode-specific quality rule produced five concrete prompts without flattening their distinct jobs. (iteration 3)\n48: - Phrase-level contract comparison and the 15-test baseline exposed regressions that thematic prompt review missed. (iteration 4)\n49: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n50: \n51: <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n52: ## 7. What Failed\n53: \n54: - Broad repository search for generic include/template terms was noisy; exact command-runtime and renderer symbols are required for the next pass. (iteration 1)\n55: - Historical compiled-stub descriptions were insufficient; direct live-command reads were required to establish the current runtime contract. (iteration 2)\n56: - A broad all-command read truncated before all five routers; exact current anchors plus the prior synthesis covered the missing comparisons, but iteration 4 must narrowly verify authority-bearing phrases against each exact router. (iteration 3)\n57: - Official documentation proves `@` content expansion but does not explicitly define the base of the exact `@./.opencode/...` spelling; the lineage-only boundary prohibits creating a scratch command outside this packet. (iteration 4)\n58: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n59: \n60: <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n61: ## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n62: \n63: - Replacing mode judgment with command-owned taste: already rejected by the authority split established in prior research.\n64: - Treating the current shared contract alone as the requested literal-prompt deliverable: contradicted by the verified gap analysis.\n65: - Wholesale router replacement: exhausted because current prerequisites, route mappings, proof outputs, and handoff boundaries are useful and should be retained. (iteration 1)\n66: - Presentation-only enrichment: exhausted because it leaves the literal command body dependent on external fragments and preserves the experiential gap. (iteration 1)\n67: - Shell-output compilation for this rewrite: exhausted as disproportionate registry, drift, security, and manifest machinery when native `@` expansion exists. (iteration 2)\n68: - Hand-duplicating the full lifecycle in five commands: exhausted because it creates normative drift without improving runtime self-containment. (iteration 2)\n69: - Applying anti-generic creative rhetoric to `design-reference`: exhausted because extraction quality is source fidelity and provenance, not originality. (iteration 3)\n70: - Wrapper-only literal enrichment while retaining presentations as normative prompt authority: exhausted because it creates competing command-package sources of truth. (iteration 4)\n71: <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n72: \n73: <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n74: ## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n75: \n76: - Command-owned palettes, typography recipes, style menus, or fixed visual doctrine: ruled out because modes own taste and design judgment. (iteration 1)\n77: - Markdown links/read imperatives and presentation/YAML assets as loader includes: ruled out because they do not provide native file-content expansion. (iteration 2)\n78: - Copying reference inventories, transport mechanics, exact palettes/fonts, token recipes, or validation procedures into command bodies: ruled out as mode/transport-owned doctrine. (iteration 3)\n79: - Dropping `STATUS=ASK`, letting audit apply fixes, or allowing brief-provided values into design-reference token tables: ruled out by shared and mode contracts. (iteration 4)\n80: <!-- /ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n81: \n82: <!-- ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n83: ## 10. Carried-Forward Open Questions\n84: \n85: - Verify the exact project-root include token in an isolated implementation fixture before merging; documentation supports `@path` inclusion but the proposed `@./.opencode/...` base remains unproven. (iteration 4)\n86: <!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n87: \n88: <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n89: ## 11. Next Focus\n90: \n91: Resolve the include token from the strongest available runtime/source evidence without violating the lineage-only write boundary, then consolidate the corrected body grammar, acceptance matrix, rollout order, risks, and residual fixture requirement for final synthesis.\n92: <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n93: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n94: \n95: ## 12. Known Context\n96: \n97: - The parent gap analysis confirms that the 002 research produced literal templates but the build shipped thin routers plus a shared lifecycle contract. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/gap-analysis.md:109-147]\n98: - The 002 synthesis defines five stable command-to-mode mappings, a nine-stage shared lifecycle, concrete short templates, and an unresolved include/shared-fragment question. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/002-research-design-commands/research/research.md:67-178] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/002-research-design-commands/research/research.md:291-300]\n99: - The target packet explicitly requires research and recommendations only; command files remain read-only. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/spec.md:50-75]\n100: - `resource-map.md` is not present in the target spec folder; skipping the input coverage gate.\n101: \n102: ## 13. Research Boundaries\n103: \n104: - Maximum iterations: 5\n105: - Stop policy: max-iterations\n106: - Convergence threshold: 0.05, telemetry only before iteration 5\n107: - Allowed write root: this detached `sol-high-fast` lineage only\n108: - Per-iteration write set: one prompt, one narrative, one delta, and one append-only state record\n109: - Workflow-owned outputs: reducer projections, resource map, and final synthesis within the lineage\n\n(End of file - total 109 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Strategy: Literal Interface Command Prompts\n\n## 1. Research Topic\n\nRewrite the five `/interface:*` commands as literal, self-contained design prompts while preserving the split where commands own intake and lifecycle, `sk-design` modes own taste and judgment, transports own realization, and `sk-code` owns application-code mutation.\n\n## 2. Non-Goals\n\n- Do not modify commands, presentation assets, skills, workflows, tests, or packet docs.\n- Do not write anywhere outside this detached `sol-high-fast` lineage.\n- Do not reopen the settled five-command namespace or stable workflow-mode mapping without contradictory evidence.\n- Do not duplicate palettes, typography prescriptions, style menus, reference inventories, or mode-owned taste doctrine into commands.\n- Do not settle unrelated styles-library structure or database-fate work.\n\n## 3. Stop Conditions\n\n- Complete exactly five iterations because `stopPolicy=max-iterations`.\n- Produce concrete, substantially self-contained command-body proposals for all five `/interface:*` commands.\n- Resolve the runtime-supported include/shared-fragment mechanism with direct repository evidence.\n- Provide a durable authority/anti-duplication rule and a testable implementation plan.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","text":"# Deep Research Strategy: Literal Interface Command Prompts\n\n## 1. Research Topic\n\nRewrite the five `/interface:*` commands as literal, self-contained design prompts while preserving the split where commands own intake and lifecycle, `sk-design` modes own taste and judgment, transports own realization, and `sk-code` owns application-code mutation.\n\n## 2. Non-Goals\n\n- Do not modify commands, presentation assets, skills, workflows, tests, or packet docs.\n- Do not write anywhere outside this detached `sol-high-fast` lineage.\n- Do not reopen the settled five-command namespace or stable workflow-mode mapping without contradictory evidence.\n- Do not duplicate palettes, typography prescriptions, style menus, reference inventories, or mode-owned taste doctrine into commands.\n- Do not settle unrelated styles-library structure or database-fate work.\n\n## 3. Stop Conditions\n\n- Complete exactly five iterations because `stopPolicy=max-iterations`.\n- Produce concrete, substantially self-contained command-body proposals for all five `/interface:*` commands.\n- Resolve the runtime-supported include/shared-fragment mechanism with direct repository evidence.\n- Provide a durable authority/anti-duplication rule and a testable implementation plan.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 4. Key Questions (Remaining)\n\n- [x] What exactly do the shipped command routers, presentation assets, and shared creation contract contain, and which literal-prompt qualities are absent?\n- [x] What complete literal body should each of the five commands contain so an agent receives an evocative, actionable creation brief rather than a thin route?\n- [x] What include, template injection, renderer, or generated-fragment mechanism does the current command runtime actually support?\n- [x] Which content must stay literal in each command, which content may be shared, and which doctrine must remain mode-owned to prevent drift?\n- [x] What exact file/change/test sequence can ship the rewrite without breaking route, intake, proof, handoff, or compatibility contracts?\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n## 5. Answered Questions\n\n- The shipped bodies preserve valuable command-specific intake, sibling discrimination, route proof, stable mode mappings, typed outputs, and mutation boundaries, but outsource the creation experience across presentations and the shared contract. The missing layer is a command-visible, evocative, actionable brief with experiential stakes, anti-generic constraints, real context/content, and a mode-specific quality bar. (iteration 1)\n- OpenCode command templates support direct `@./path` file-content expansion. The recommended mechanism is literal, mode-specific creation prose in each command plus one `@./.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/creation-contract.md` expansion for shared normative lifecycle and authority content. This yields runtime-expanded self-containment; checked-in source-byte duplication would require generation and is unnecessary. (iteration 2)\n- Five concrete body cores now define the command-visible mission, intake, grounding, stable route, ordered work, targeted revision, proof ceiling, typed output, and handoff for design, foundations, motion, audit, and design-reference. Public orchestration stays literal, universal schemas arrive through the shared `@` contract, and values/judgment remain mode-owned. (iteration 3)\n- Adversarial review preserved the missions and mode-specific quality rules but moved universal intake schemas, common blocks, targeted revision, evidence labels, and handoff continuity back to the shared contract. It restored `ASK`, required literal suffix control, made audit review-only, and restricted design-reference token tables to measured values. The safe shipment is test-first and atomic across wrappers, presentation/YAML ownership declarations, and metadata projections. (iteration 4)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n## 6. What Worked\n\n- Exact cross-command anchor comparison separated the shared routing skeleton from meaningful domain-specific intake and exposed the missing prompt layer without discarding working architecture. (iteration 1)\n- Exact command-authoring and renderer-symbol tracing distinguished native `@` expansion, `$ARGUMENTS` substitution, shell rendering, and generated-router patterns. (iteration 2)\n- A common mission-to-handoff grammar plus one decisive mode-specific quality rule produced five concrete prompts without flattening their distinct jobs. (iteration 3)\n- Phrase-level contract comparison and the 15-test baseline exposed regressions that thematic prompt review missed. (iteration 4)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n## 7. What Failed\n\n- Broad repository search for generic include/template terms was noisy; exact command-runtime and renderer symbols are required for the next pass. (iteration 1)\n- Historical compiled-stub descriptions were insufficient; direct live-command reads were required to establish the current runtime contract. (iteration 2)\n- A broad all-command read truncated before all five routers; exact current anchors plus the prior synthesis covered the missing comparisons, but iteration 4 must narrowly verify authority-bearing phrases against each exact router. (iteration 3)\n- Official documentation proves `@` content expansion but does not explicitly define the base of the exact `@./.opencode/...` spelling; the lineage-only boundary prohibits creating a scratch command outside this packet. (iteration 4)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n\n- Replacing mode judgment with command-owned taste: already rejected by the authority split established in prior research.\n- Treating the current shared contract alone as the requested literal-prompt deliverable: contradicted by the verified gap analysis.\n- Wholesale router replacement: exhausted because current prerequisites, route mappings, proof outputs, and handoff boundaries are useful and should be retained. (iteration 1)\n- Presentation-only enrichment: exhausted because it leaves the literal command body dependent on external fragments and preserves the experiential gap. (iteration 1)\n- Shell-output compilation for this rewrite: exhausted as disproportionate registry, drift, security, and manifest machinery when native `@` expansion exists. (iteration 2)\n- Hand-duplicating the full lifecycle in five commands: exhausted because it creates normative drift without improving runtime self-containment. (iteration 2)\n- Applying anti-generic creative rhetoric to `design-reference`: exhausted because extraction quality is source fidelity and provenance, not originality. (iteration 3)\n- Wrapper-only literal enrichment while retaining presentations as normative prompt authority: exhausted because it creates competing command-package sources of truth. (iteration 4)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n\n- Command-owned palettes, typography recipes, style menus, or fixed visual doctrine: ruled out because modes own taste and design judgment. (iteration 1)\n- Markdown links/read imperatives and presentation/YAML assets as loader includes: ruled out because they do not provide native file-content expansion. (iteration 2)\n- Copying reference inventories, transport mechanics, exact palettes/fonts, token recipes, or validation procedures into command bodies: ruled out as mode/transport-owned doctrine. (iteration 3)\n- Dropping `STATUS=ASK`, letting audit apply fixes, or allowing brief-provided values into design-reference token tables: ruled out by shared and mode contracts. (iteration 4)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n## 10. Carried-Forward Open Questions\n\n- Verify the exact project-root include token in an isolated implementation fixture before merging; documentation supports `@path` inclusion but the proposed `@./.opencode/...` base remains unproven. (iteration 4)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n## 11. Next Focus\n\nResolve the include token from the strongest available runtime/source evidence without violating the lineage-only write boundary, then consolidate the corrected body grammar, acceptance matrix, rollout order, risks, and residual fixture requirement for final synthesis.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n\n## 12. Known Context\n\n- The parent gap analysis confirms that the 002 research produced literal templates but the build shipped thin routers plus a shared lifecycle contract. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/gap-analysis.md:109-147]\n- The 002 synthesis defines five stable command-to-mode mappings, a nine-stage shared lifecycle, concrete short templates, and an unresolved include/shared-fragment question. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/002-research-design-commands/research/research.md:67-178] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/002-research-design-commands/research/research.md:291-300]\n- The target packet explicitly requires research and recommendations only; command files remain read-only. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/spec.md:50-75]\n- `resource-map.md` is not present in the target spec folder; skipping the input coverage gate.\n\n## 13. Research Boundaries\n\n- Maximum iterations: 5\n- Stop policy: max-iterations\n- Convergence threshold: 0.05, telemetry only before iteration 5\n- Allowed write root: this detached `sol-high-fast` lineage only\n- Per-iteration write set: one prompt, one narrative, one delta, and one append-only state record\n- Workflow-owned outputs: reducer projections, resource map, and final synthesis within the lineage","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":109,"totalLines":109,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/004-commands/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1784626472498,"end":1784626472558}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0201d8e03d6151bd016a5f3d2830588191814ae6bb66a2a6f9"}},"id":"prt_f8406e62d001LL3Uez7cnNjb3D","sessionID":"ses_07c1fcf6effe2YUDoq6jbB4HYf","messageID":"msg_f84068f1e001277goGF4Jwuu3r"}}
